message.content: Notice that when factoring we can group terms with common factors, effectively using Simon's Favorite Factorization. In this case, move all the terms with $y$ to one side of the equation by adding $20$ to both sides: \[xy+5x+4y+20 = 15.\] Notice that $xy+5x$ can be factored: \[x(y+5) = -4(y+5).\] Hence, $(y+5)(x+4) = 0$. So either $y+5 = 0$, or $x+4 = 0$, giving $y = \boxed{-5}$.
